{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526623"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:23:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:23:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14144"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14144"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.14,0.49,0.13,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89835"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6824"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14144"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74026"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3339"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18012"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44308"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89835"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of fever, sore throat, and fatigue. She has a medical history of treatment-resistant schizophrenia and has been taking clozapine for the past six months. She does not take any other regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Oropharyngeal examination reveals erythema and white patches on the tonsils. Investigations reveal a white blood cell count of 1.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0) with an absolute neutrophil count of 0.2 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (2.0-7.5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat Full Blood Count due to aberrant result","Continue clozapine and start antibiotics","Discontinue clozapine","Reduce clozapine dose by 50% and monitor closely","Reduce clozapine dose and administer G-CSF"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and laboratory findings consistent with agranulocytosis, a potentially life-threatening side effect of clozapine. The most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ediscontinue clozapine\u003C/strong\u003E. Clozapine-induced agranulocytosis is defined as an absolute neutrophil count (ANC) below 0.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L, which is seen in this case (0.2 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L). Immediate discontinuation of clozapine is crucial to prevent further bone marrow suppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat Full Blood Count due to aberrant result\u003C/strong\u003E would delay necessary treatment. While laboratory errors can occur, the patient\u0027s clinical presentation is consistent with agranulocytosis, and immediate action is required based on the current results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue clozapine and start antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially dangerous. While antibiotics may be necessary to treat any ongoing infection, continuing clozapine in the face of agranulocytosis could lead to further deterioration of the patient\u0027s condition and increase the risk of severe infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduce clozapine dose by 50% and monitor closely\u003C/strong\u003E is not sufficient in this case. Agranulocytosis is a severe adverse effect that requires immediate discontinuation of the drug, not just dose reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduce clozapine dose and administer G-CSF\u003C/strong\u003E is also inappropriate. While granulocyte colony-stimulating factor (G-CSF) may be used to stimulate neutrophil production in severe agranulocytosis, it should only be administered after clozapine has been completely discontinued, not with a reduced dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter discontinuing clozapine, the next steps would include starting G-CSF to stimulate neutrophil production, providing supportive care, including broad-spectrum antibiotics if there\u0027s suspicion of infection, and possibly reverse isolation to protect against opportunistic infections. Close monitoring of blood counts is essential until recovery. Once the agranulocytosis resolves, an alternative antipsychotic medication will need to be considered for managing the patient\u0027s schizophrenia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Clozapine-induced agranulocytosis is a potentially life-threatening condition requiring immediate discontinuation of the drug.","Granulocyte colony-stimulating factor (G-CSF) can be used to stimulate neutrophil production in severe cases of agranulocytosis.","Regular monitoring of white blood cell count and absolute neutrophil count is crucial for patients on clozapine therapy."],"references":["Castle DJ, Galletly CA, Dark F, Humberstone V, Morgan VA, Killackey E, Kulkarni J, McGorry P, Nielssen O, Tran NT, Jablensky A. The 2016 Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatrists guidelines for the management of schizophrenia and related disorders. Medical Journal of Australia. 2017 Jun;206(11):501-5.","Mijovic A, MacCabe JH. Clozapine-induced agranulocytosis. Ann Hematol. 2020 Nov;99(11):2477-2482. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7536144/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74026"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14144"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74026"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T08:23:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T13:25:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6824"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89835"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergen